Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Mauritius Commercial Bank, Stanbic IBTC of Kenya

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-11T15:49:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-11/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-mauritius-commercial-bank-stanbic.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index gained 0.6
percent to 2,040.67 at the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , the
highest since Feb. 21.  Kenya’s All-Share Index rose 0.6 percent to 75.02 at the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi, the highest in a month. The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index fell 1.9 percent to 1,043.69 at 3 p.m.
in Accra. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index slipped
0.2 percent to 24,675.75 by the 3 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to an e-mailed statement from the bourse. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  added less than 0.1 percent to 898.15 by 5 p.m. in
Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mauritius Commercial Bank (MCB)  , the Indian Ocean island
nation’s largest lender by market value, rose 2.3 percent to 176
rupees, the highest price since Feb. 16, after saying it reached
a settlement with Mauritius Union Assurance Co. over claims and
counterclaims lodged by the companies.  Stanbic IBTC Bank Plc (IBTCCB)  , a Nigerian lender,
gained 35 kobo, or 4 percent, to 9.06 naira, the most in more
than two weeks, on speculation loans increased in the first
quarter through March, boosting profit, according to Vetiva
Capital Management Ltd. Stanbic is expected to increase loans by
7 percent to 8 percent, “and that will be positive for
earnings,” Abiola Razaq, a Lagos-based banking analyst at
Vetiva, said by phone. Results are expected on April 13 or 14,
he said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
